1.15.3.2 UNDERSTANDING OF SCOPE OF WORK

1.15.3.2.1 UNDERSTANDING CONTRACT REQUIREMENTS

Contract Requirements: The project involves the design, construction, operation and maintenance of a new Travel Time (TT) System by replacing the existing TT system on multiple highway corridors in MTO Central Region, Ontario. The travel time information will be displayed on MTO owned VMS to assist the public to find out the travel time along alternate routes and plan their route selections accordingly as well as reducing congestion in work zones and around incidents.

B&M understands that at the end of Operation, Maintenance and Support Phase, MTO may exercise the optional extension of the TT Service for two (2) additional years. B&M understands that once awarded B&M shall coordinate the work with other Contractors within and/or adjacent to the contract limits to ensure that we do not perform work in the same area at the same time, or adversely affect each others work. B&M understands that Travel time data sharing agreements with additional partner agencies may be reached during the Term of Agreement, in which case B&M shall collaborate with the partner agencys travel time service provider to receive and generate the travel time information for new TT destinations.

B&M understands that MTO is responsible for displaying travel time information on the VMS as well as that the existing TT System must remain in operation until the new system is ready to Go-Live. B&M understands that due to COVID-19 pandemic, B&M shall comply with local public health guidelines and recommendations that are in effect at the time. B&M understands that other ongoing capital contracts may take precedence over the work required under this contract as determined by the MTO RWSCU.

Scope of Work: This RFP seeks to develop and implement a TT system that helps the public make informed route selection decisions, take advantage of faster alternate routes, and reduce congestion along congested roads. The TT Service consists of the following components:

1. Bluetooth (BT) Readers that includes all their mounting, power and communications infrastructure and services required for operation of the BT units and as described in the RFP document;

2. TT System Solution that will process the real-time detection data and field equipment status and generate travel times for the specified road segments; and

3. Internet service that allows the MTO central system to retrieve TT data for VMS publication.

B&M installed server will receive the raw data collected from the BT and will be responsible to transform it into TT information, data storage and hosting. B&M server will format the processed TT information into three (3) data feeds, in accordance with MTO data specifications:

         Link-based TT TT between two adjacent BT;

         Route-based TT TT between VMS and the displayed destination;

         Sign-based TT message for each destination defined for VMS

MTO's Central Region's COMPASS System/Software shall be able to receive these data feeds through a secure channel, representing the demarcation point between the B&Ms system and MTO's system. These mentioned data feeds will also be made available with MTOs other travel time servers and partner agencies. Travel time information for Central Regions VMS that display TT for destinations outside of Central Region, is subscribed to the server from select partner agencies. Data dictionary of the partner agencies TT systems will be adjusted to match the data dictionary required by this contract.

Services to be delivered: B&M is responsible to provide, host, and manage a TT System Graphical User Interface (GUI) for MTO users to access. B&M will be responsible for developing a Test Plan including Pre-Installation Testing (PIT), Proof of Performance (POP), System Integration Testing (SIT), Pilot Demonstration Testing (PDT) and System Acceptance Testing (SAT). B&M Team will supply with all required equipment, housing, power provisions, mounting hardware and infrastructure, and the digital cellular data services for the duration of the TT Service Contract

Once awarded, B&M will supply an external power disconnect to enable isolation of the Bluetooth equipment without access to the cabinet. B&M will select the size, electrical design and environmental enclosure to meet the equipment needs and the requirements of current edition of Canadian Electrical Code CSA C22.1 and will supply liquid tight flexible conduit and fittings to enclose all external wiring. B&M Team will design the solar power supplies to meet the operation requirements of the Bluetooth Reader and the cellular communication device. B&M will conform to OPSS 609 and all standards referenced in RFP for installation of electrical grounding equipment. At locations where, external cable access enclosure is not present, B&M shall supply and install the new enclosure according to the requirements. The Bluetooth Readers and all associated components will be securely mounted to the poles or unistrut to withstand its own load, winter ice and wind loading in the installation area. The existing Bluetooth equipment and all associated infrastructure components as listed in Appendix C will be removed, except the support structures being used for the new deployment, specifically the wooden posts at existing controller cabinets. B&M Team will host a Network Time Protocol (NTP) solution to accurately synchronize time between the MTO systems, the TT System, and the BT Readers.

1.15.3.2.3 Innovative Approach

Our Project Teams proposal and fees includes the following innovative approaches, above the provided specifications.

 

Included within the price and proposal, are the following innovative approaches:

 

Open Protocol Sensor

 

The Stinson AIS sensor uses a published and open protocol which allows any third-party software provider to integrate the raw sensor data output. As such, end users are not locked into a single software vendor. If MTO chooses, they could opt to use an alternative software platform in the future for travel time calculations. For instance, Genetec - MTOs video management system - is already integrated with Stinson AIS.

 

Improved Detection Functionality

 

Additional detection: Beyond basic Bluetooth detection, the proposed solution will allow for higher detection and data through additional detection of;

         Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) Devices: our field testing indicates that BLE offers 20x the number of detections compared to Bluetooth alone

         Wi-Fi device detection: Our field testing indicates that Wi-Fi device detection offers 5x more detections than Bluetooth alone.

 

In additional to the increased data and device detection capability, having both Wi-Fi and Bluetooth sensors allows for built in redundancy; if the Bluetooth module fails, then the Wi-Fi sensor will continue to function, and vice versa.

 

This functionality is included within the proposed bid price and proposal

 

Innovative Software Interface

 

Some additional functionality of the software, above the stated specifications, include

 

         Full web-based sensor management interface, allowing for an operator to easily maintain, troubleshoot, and reconfigure the sensor

         Full VMS Management Interface; ITS Central will allow for pixel-by-pixel preview of the messages, to illustrate exactly how the sign message will be posted. This is superior to a text-only display

         Quick and easy creation of virtual VMSs to evaluate and envision travel time message displays at new VMS locations

         Integration with existing Ontario 511 data (cameras, road conditions, constructions and incidents) into the same map interface for full situational awareness of what is happening on the roads. It put the current travel time data in context.

         Integration with Environment Canada precipitation (rain/snow) and radar imagery as an overlay for additional situational awareness.

 

 

PROJECT COST CONTROL

B&M utilizes a well-defined and monitored job cost control system using Oracles JD Edwards (JDE) which acts as an early warning system to enable the Project Manager to review live project financials at any given moment, unlike some elaborate systems which provide little more than historical data long after opportunities for value engineering have passed. B&M objectives of job cost control for tracking and maintaining project budgets include:

  To monitor planned, incurred and anticipated project expenditures;

  To control the cost of construction;

  To provide ongoing forecasts of the projects financial outcome; and

  To maintain effective records which provide the results of good and bad estimates so that adjustments can be made in labour productivity factors, and project methodology

To accomplish the objectives, specific job control steps are undertaken within our accounting software to measure actual performance versus planned performance, and to identify variances in time needed to make appropriate corrections. Criteria include Labour hours, Materials, Equipment or (Major Material), Consumables, Direct Job expenses, Subcontracts, Rentals, and Cash Allowances.

 

Productivity Strategy

Manpower productivity is managed using JD Edwards (JDE) and MS Project scheduling software. Once an estimate is finalized and all associated scope of work is captured, our accounting team uploads the estimated costs for all the labour, equipment and materials into our JDE software. As scope of work in the field is executed, the quantities are captured on a daily basis and compared with schedule requirements and productivity estimates. B&M analyzes this data and determines next steps. B&M will continuously strive for increased productivity to ensure milestone and end dates are achieved or improved from planned turn over.

 

Change Management

B&M uses JDE to track and manage the change management process for all projects. Change Requests contain important information regarding a potential customer Change Order including; brief description, reference numbers, associated dates and all required adjustments to estimated man-hours, cost and revenue which impact the overall budget of a job. Change Orders should always be entered into JD Edwards at a submitted status before the quote letter is submitted to the customer. This ensures that quoted Change Order amounts are visible on the Job Status Inquiry and on certain Job Reports. Once approval or a proceed notice is received from the customer it is critical that the required status updates are completed in JD Edwards to ensure that correct job forecasting of cost and revenue is maintained. It is important to follow this process to ensure all changes in the Contract are budgeted, costed, forecast and billed.

Revision Control Issues

The revision control system and revision control history ensures a capability to quickly revert faulty changes of a new deployment that has proven to be problematic. This is done using the systems diff feature. Transnomis utilizes the industry-standard tool GIT.

Critical System Code Issues

Critical system functions (such as security functions, control logic functions, and interlock safety functions) are all reviewed twice once by a senior developer and once by the software manager. Code Integration Issues

The Transnomis technical team practices Continuous Integration (CI). Developers merge their code into a shared repository (trunk) several times a day and the code in each merge is tested using automated testing. The CI process is supported by the use of popular tools like Jenkins, MS Test, Selenium, Nunit and Zalenium. 

Once the preliminary stage of build and unit testing is completed, Jenkins then triggers automated test cases where Component Testing, Smoke Testing, Integration Testing, and Regression Testing are performed. 

 

Device Integration issues

A test server is set up with a modest set of data, integrated devices, and an integration of a subset of open data sources at a significantly lower polling frequency. Test servers help detect software integration issues prior to deployment into any production environment. These servers not only allow for manual testing of various web pages requiring user inputs, they also provide a platform for any new developments and full integration testing for gateway processes.  

Modular and GUI Integration Issues

A staging server is set up with clients sample datasets and configurations. A staging server will be set up to test all relevant software modules and graphical user interfaces before deployment to production.

Module Failure

All Transnomis software modules are covered by automated software issue logging and alerts. Should a module fail and/or crash, the software will automatically log it as an issue into the database and will send out a notification email to Transnomis Solutions staff. Issues are often resolved even before the end-user notices them.  Actions taken to resolve the software issue are tracked and logged.

System Testing

Comprehensive System Testing will also mitigate risks of software errors and issues. The project will undergo comprehensive testing, in adherence with standard MTO processes. A formal Test plan will be prepared and submitted for review and approval that will document the tests to be performed and the expected results. The OE and MTO will be invited to all testing as witnesses, and test results will be documented and submitted at the completion of all tests.

 

         PIT and POP Testing: Pre-Installation Testing (PIT) will include all PIT tests required in the Special Provision for each ATMS element, and will be conducted prior to the installation of the components. After installation, Proof of Performance (POP) testing will test each component and subsystem individually, confirming that the unit meets the performance standards. Central Software will be tested for central software functionality only, without connecting to field devices. These tests will specifically address the special provision paragraphs requiring POP testing as listed in the quality control section for each item.

 

         System Integration Testing (SIT): When all POP testing is completed, and every element of the system is operational, the system can undergo System Integration Testing (SIT) to ensure that the entire system operates correctly when it is fully online. This testing will verify the operation of the communication subsystem as a standalone subsystem, and then independently verify the Traffic Sensor Solution subsystem and VMS subsystems operating over the communication subsystem. When all subsystems are confirmed, the next stage of testing will confirm the operation of all equipment operating at the same time. Finally, fail safe testing will test the operation of redundant communication systems (fiber rings and backup LTE modem connections) to ensure that the operation continues seamlessly during a simulated failure. Central Software will be used to control and check the statuses of the field hardware. The field hardware devices will then be tested to ensure they perform the physical actions as expected (e.g., activation of VMS messages, etc.).

 

         Pre-OPT Calibration Period: Pre-OPT calibration period will allow for iterative optimization of the overall automation and look for opportunities to adjust device firmware settings and improve algorithms /parameters with the goal of reducing false positive and false negatives.

 

         End to End Test (E2E): This End to End Test will test that the field conditions trigger the correct messaging on the field devices. Where practical and safe, field conditions will be recreated.

1.15.3.4 SYSTEM COMPONENTS, PRODUCT AND SYSTEM CONCEPT

1.15.3.4.1 System Concept

 

This Travel Time system will gather data from Bluetooth and Wifi detectors. The data will be transmitted to ITS Central control software, and be used to estimate travel times along roadways within the scope area, between detectors, and between specified origin destination pairs. Additional travel time data will be received from interjurisdictional partners, and processed by ITS Central. The link based data and route based data will be transmitted in a VPS feed, along with sign based message data, to MTO.

 

General System Architecture

Above is an overview diagram depicting our proposed vision of the general system architecture.

Stinson AIS Bluetooth and WiFi Detectors will collect data from the field, and transmit that data to the ITS Central software, via an LTE network connection.

The entirety of the ITS Central software is proposed to be hosted by a third-party hosting service, OVH, providing triple redundant servers and failover. The third-party hosting will be provided for within the scope of this proposal, and managed by Transnomis.

The field data (hashed MAC addresses) will be received by the ITS Centrals Traffic Sensor Module, processed by the Travel Time Gateway module into travel time information and relevant statistics, and stored in the ITS Central database. Travel time information from the interjurisdictional partner agencies, will be received and processed through ITS Centrals TPANA Travel Time Gateway, for links and routes that cross MTO Central Region boundaries.

Transnomis will work with MTO and its Owners Engineer to create a secure VPN data feed for the transfer of the travel time information to the MTOs Central Region COMPASS system and software, and to other MTO partner agencies. The processed data will meet the MTO data specifications and the data dictionary provided. The three data feeds will from ITS Centrals Travel Time REST API, and will comprise of:

         Link based Travel Times, on routes between adjacent sensors

         Route based Travel Times, between VMS and the specified destination(s)

         Sign based Travel Times messages for each destination defined for VMS

The ITS Central GUI will allow for MTOs system users and system administrators to interact with the system, via a web browser. The ITS Central GUI includes, but is not limited to, the following functionality:

         A configurable dashboard

         Monitoring of the field devices

         Reporting on current data and travel times

         Retrieval of historical data

         Configuration of device parameters, notification contacts, and system parameters

Using the information provided in the RFP, Transnomis has already configured all of the Bluetooth sensor locations and meta-data, as well as VMS locations:

MTO will receive the data feeds, and can use the data to display travel time information on VMS. Future data sharing agreements may be reached during the Term of Agreement, per Article 3.

Concept of Operations

The following provides a synopsis of the concept of operations

         The sensors will read the MAC addresses of detected devices (Bluetooth & Wi-Fi) as they pass through the sensors detection radius (minimum 100m).

         Device MAC addresses are hashed and encrypted and sent to ITS Central software instance via local LTE modem connection

         ITS Central receives hashed MAC addresses continuously from all sensors and processes the data into matches in order to calculate link travel time data (Link Data: Matches between two adjacent sensors).

         ITS Central received travel time link data from the partner agencies.

         Link data is combined to calculate the configured route times (a route is a combination of adjacent segments) as required for the three types of travel times (link-based, route based, and sign based).

         Travel time data is stored and the three types of travel times are provided to the MTO via the XML feed API interface through a secured VPN tunnel.

         MTO receives the data feeds, and uses the data for VMS displays. MTO also is able to access further data and configure/monitor devices via the web browser GUI.

 

1.15.3.4.2 Infrastructure Components and Product Cut Sheets

Functional Specifications of TT System Related Infrastructure Components & Cut Sheets

Integrated All-In-One Bluetooth Reader: Stinson AIS Bluetooth, Bluetooth Low Energy & Wi-Fi Detection Sensor

 

These devices are integrated into a non-metallic enclosure to provide the integrated all-in-one solution The Ministry has requested.

They will utilize external weatherproof omni directional antennas for long range and robust detection for highway environments. Each transceiver will have a dedicated antenna (1 for Bluetooth, 1 for Wi-Fi) in order to maximize detection quality.

While our standard aluminum enclosure is shown below for the purposes of this tender the device components will be housed in a non-metallic enclosure as has been requested.

 

The Stinson AIS is a versatile sensor which supports Bluetooth, Bluetooth Low Energy and WiFi detection.  While detection rates from a single transceiver are fairly uniform across vendors the Stinson AIS outperforms them by incorporating multiple transceivers in a single unit; our standard configuration is 1x Bluetooth transceiver and 1x WiFi transceiver.  This allows for scanning multiple frequency channels at the same time and communicating with multiple devices simultaneously.  With the addition of WiFi detection the Ministry will be able to capture 2-3 times as many devices as Bluetooth only devices.   

 

Bluetooth sensors are traditionally similar in their feature sets and performance characteristics and what differentiates them is their ease of installation in various environments as well as the simplicity of configuration.  Below are some of the key attributes which set our sensor apart: 

 

Key Features:

 

         Supports three antenna types: Low powered Omni (100m range), high powered Omni (200m range), and Directional antenna (300m range) 

         Diverse Power Supply options.  Can be powered by a standard 120V AC outlet, any 9-36V DC power source, or via Power-Over-Ethernet. 

         On-board SD card for data redundancy and backup. Data self-heals upon reconnect.

         NTP Time sync support

         Open-Protocol Sensor utilizes an open-protocol firmware such that any ATMS/CMS system can integrate its protocol and receive raw detection data directly. The Ministry will not be locked into a single software vendor for travel time processing, the Stinson AIS has been integrated into a number of ATMS systems including: (1) Transnomis ITS Central and (2) Genetec Travel Time Engine  

 

Compact Shelf Mount Unit: 

 

Stinsons shelf mount unit combines all of our hardware features into a compact enclosure.  This unit integrates an onboard wide input power supply (9-36VDC) as well as passive Power over Ethernet support.  PoE support means only a single cable is required to connect the unit, making install easier.  Its small form factor makes it ideal for traffic cabinet & PVMS mounting.  Units can be ordered with an AC or DC PoE injector. 

 

Technical Specifications:

MTO Third-Party Tested: 

 

The Stinson AIS participated in an MTO project in 2016 to test a variety of alternative Bluetooth detection devices to determine their accuracy and penetration rates. This testing was performed on Hwy 26 near Wasaga Beach and involved three vendor devices: Iteris Vantage, ISS Deep Blue, and the Stinson AIS. WSP performed the testing and evaluation which focused on the Accuracy and Penetration rate of each sensor to determine if they met industry standards. The results of the testing confirmed that the Stinson AIS met industry standards for both metrics and as such were well suited for travel time applications on roadways.

 

Ease of Installation: 

 

When designing the Stinson AIS, ease of installation and configuration were two key factors we focused on throughout the process.  With this in mind, we developed two sensor variants for installation in any environment:

 

         a compact shelf mount unit when cabinet space is critical  

         a standalone weatherproof pole mount unit when no cabinet or infrastructure is available (Not included)

 

To further ease the simplicity of installation we have designed a flexible power supply system which makes it possible to install this device nearly anywhere.  While hardwiring is possible most of our sensors are powered using Power Over Ethernet (POE), this means the power and data comes over a single Ethernet cable into the unit. This simplifies installation as there are only two cables to plug in; the Ethernet cable and the antenna cable.  Our POE system can get power from: 

         120VAC Outlet/supply 

         DC supply of 9 to 36V 

         Standard 802.3at/af POE network switch or midspan (adapter required, not included)

 

Ease of Configuration:

 

The Stinson AIS is very easy to configure, all configurations are done through a very user-friendly web interface (Screenshot below).  For normal operation the only setting that needs to be configured is the IP Address & NTP server.  Our unit supports DHCP as well as Static IP addressing.  Using the default IP address, it is very easy to access the web interface using any web browser.  From there you can enter the device IP and the configuration is complete. 

 

Additional settings that can be changed in the unit are related to MAC address encryption, Network time sync and firmware upgrades.  You can also remotely reset the unit from this interface. 

 

 

Cellular Modem: MicroHard BulletLTE NA2

 

MicroHard modems will be configured with a firewall and other security settings to prevent unauthorized network access. The devices will also be monitored by ITS Central to ensure normal operation and alerts will be triggered if the modem goes offline or becomes non-responsive for any reason. We employ IP whitelisting, firewall port rules, ping blocking and limiting of some network diagnostic requests to secure the device. This helps prevent DDOS attacks and other types of nuisance traffic & intrusion attempts.

 

Stinson ITS Solar System

Stinson will be supplying solar systems for all of the standalone sites that are called for in this project. Stinson has been designing and manufacturing solar systems for over 7 years and has extensive experience. The systems supplied shall be intentionally over-sized in order to provide exceptional performance and near zero regular maintenance. The system will provide 12 days of autonomy and will utilize a solar panel twice as large as is needed such that it can fully charge even in cloudy conditions or when the panel is partially covered in snow. The system utilizes an MPPT solar controller which allows for charging during the above-mentioned challenging conditions when solar voltage is not optimal. The solar panel will also be mounted at a very steep angle (75-90 degrees) in order to ensure rapid shedding of any snow accumulation. The system includes separate fuses for the batteries, load and solar panel allowing for easy de-energization for service and maintenance.

Server Hosting

For hosting, we propose the services of OVH (https://www.ovh.com/). It is one of the largest internet hosting companies in the world, with 400,000 servers, 33 data centers in 4 continents and 1.6 million customers. It is fully certified:

         PCI DSS

         ISO/IEC 27001, 27017, 27018, 27701, 50001

         SOC 1, SOC 2 and SOC 3

         Cloud Security Alliance STAR certified

OVH.com has a data center in Beauharnois, QC. Its facility is highly secure with access only by authorized employees. It has technician and security on-site 24/7. It has systematic double power supply, 250 kVA UPS and generators with an initial autonomy of 48 hours. It has a minimum of 2 network connections and two network rooms within each of its data centers. For more information, please see https://www.ovh.com/ca/en/about-us/datacenters.xml

As part of the contract, Transnomis Solutions will procure three dedicated servers with OVH data center in Beauharnois, QC. One server will be the primary server hosting the ITS Central application. The second (fail-over) server will be used for live streaming replication, which will be ready to take over immediately should the primary server fails. The third server will also have live streaming replication serving as hot spare.

Although hosting is provided by reliable third party, Transnomis Solutions is fully responsible for the availability of its software service. The Ministry will never have to deal with the hosting company. Transnomis Solutions will be the single point of contact for all issues related to services provided for this contract, including server availability issues.

Detailed Software Compliance

General System Overview (2.6.5.1)

1.1. The Solution shall receive raw data from Bluetooth Readers deployed in the field.

Transnomis ITS Central software is currently installed as the Advanced Traffic Management System in the City of Edmonton, Region of York, Region of Durham, MTO East Region, and BC Ferries. In addition, ITS Central is the control software being used for MTOs Queue and Stopped Vehicle Advisory System (QSVAS) on Highway 405, which is currently in the Operational Performance Test (OPT) period. ITS Central specializes in retrieving data and device status information from the field devices its integrated with, including the Stinson AIS Bluetooth/WiFi sensor, cellular modems, CCTV cameras, variable message signs, vehicle detectors, traffic signals, and various weather detection equipment (e.g., atmospheric sensors, wind meters, pavement sensors, etc.).

 

1.2. The Solution shall process the raw data into travel time information as per the MTO defined formats.

ITS Central is able to process the raw data (MAC addresses retrieved from the sensors) into travel time information, per the MTO defined formats. 

 

 

1.3. The Solution shall publish the travel time information as secured data feeds.

ITS Central publishes processed data to an XML file using HTTPS secured data feeds. See Requirement 5.3.1 for examples of the XML feed output.

 

 

1.4. The data feeds shall be made accessible to MTO through a secure data transmission channel.

ITS Central publishes data feeds to an XML file using HTTPS and access may be restricted to those with a valid login to the system.  Transnomis will also work with MTO to establish a secured VPN Tunnel for the data feeds, allowing for an additional layer of security.

 

1.5. The Solution shall publish the travel time information as a secured public API for future system integration and data sharing within MTO and with other jurisdictions specified by MTO.

Per above, ITS Central publishes processed data to an XML file using HTTPS secured data feeds, allowing for a secured public API for future system integration and data sharing within MTO and with other jurisdictions.  Permissions may be granted by the system administrator for access to the secured data feeds. 

 

System Configuration and Operations (2.6.5.2)

2.1. The Solution shall be configured to operate using the metric system of measurement.

ITS Central will be configured for metric by default. ITS Central supports both metric and imperial units as user preference.

 

2.2. The Solution shall be scalable to accommodate the future expansion of the TT System, including geographic expansion, and the addition of Readers, routes, and VMSs, by continuing to provide the same level of service. Details of future hardware expansions are described in Section 8.

ITS Central is designed to be fully scalable, to include future geographic expansion and inclusion of additional routes.  In addition, adding additional Bluetooth readers and VMSs is a common request by our previous clients, and can be easily accommodated.

 

 

2.3. The Solution shall operate and publish real-time travel time data feeds continuously (i.e. 24/7, 365 days).

Our ITS Central software is designed to operate continuously, 24/7/365.  Our ITS Central Advanced Traffic Management Systems in the City of Edmonton, Region of York, Region of Durham, MTO East Region, and BC Ferries operate continuously (24/7/365). MTOs QSVAS is also designed for continuous operations.  Our systems in Toronto, Oklahoma, and California are also running 24/7/365.

 

High availability features, and redundancy are designed within our proposed system, including triple servers, failover, device monitoring.

 

2.4. The Solution shall have a continuous monthly uptime of at minimum 99% outside of any scheduled and routine maintenance.

Professional third-party hosting, and triple servers are proposed to achieve 99% uptime, with an expected uptime of better than 99.99% excluding scheduled maintenance. A total of 3 servers, hosted professionally by OVH within Canada, will be utilized in this project to achieve full system triple redundancy and fail-over. OVH has technician and security on-site 24/7. It has systematic double power supply, 250 kVA UPS and generators with an initial autonomy of 48 hours. It has a minimum of 2 network connections and two network rooms within each of its data centers.

 

System uptime will also be monitored by a third-party service UptimeRobot. It provides notification to Transnomis should the system to be detected as offline. See below uptime monitoring of MTO East Visibility Warning System, showing 100% uptime over last 30 days.

 

2.5. The Solution shall have backup or redundancy procedures in place in order to resume normal operations upon system failure.

A total of 3 servers, hosted professionally by OVH within Canada, will be utilized in this project to achieve full system triple redundancy and fail-over.  Servers will be monitored, and notifications sent to Transnomis upon failure.   Field devices will be monitored, and notifications sent to B&M upon device failure.  Crashes are monitored and logged in the system.  Transnomis will review all errors logged into the system to ensure good system performance.  

 

ITS Central provides an interface for system administrators to create and download backups. This can easily be performed prior to any software updates.

 

 

2.6. The Proponent shall provide remote access to the TT System Graphical User Interface (GUI) to authorized MTO users in a secured manner.

Transnomis ITS Central software allows for browser- based access, secured by HTTPS, password- based login, and user group permissions. 

 

User rights are managed by user groups, and users are assigned to one or more user groups. The permissions the user has is the aggregation of all of the permissions of the groups the user belongs to.

 

 

2.7. The GUI shall be compatible with Microsoft Edge Version 88 or later, and Google Chrome Version 79 or later.

ITS Central is compatible with all current browsers including Microsoft Edge Version 88 or later, Google Chrome Version 79 or later.  ITS Central is also compatible with Firefox, Opera and Safari. 

 

 

2.8. At minimum, the GUI shall consist of the following four (4) modules: Travel Time Dashboard (see Section 2.6.5.6); Historical Data Portal (see Section 2.6.5.5.5); Reporting System (see Section 2.6.5.7); and System Parameter Configuration (see Section 2.6.5.10).

Among other modules, a Travel Time Dashboard, Historical Data Portal, Reporting System, and System Parameter Configuration modules are included within ITS Central.

ITS Central has been used by over a hundred users concurrently (e.g., Municipal511 is used by over 200 Ontario municipalities) with hundreds of gigabytes of data, with no adverse effects.

Device Integration (2.6.5.4)

4.2 Each VMS shall be assigned a unique ID value for identification purposes by the Solution, which shall match the VMSs ID assigned by MTO (see Appendix C).

Each VMS will be assigned a unique ID value for identification purposes by the Solution, which shall match the VMSs ID assigned by MTO

 

4.3 Bluetooth reader operational failures and losses of communication with the Solution shall be automatically logged for reporting and auditing purposes.

The operational failures and losses of communication will be logged for each Bluetooth reader.   All field devices that are monitored retain a log that can be accessed through ITS Centrals Issues tab.

 

 

4.4 Data stored internally on a Bluetooth reader collected in the event of an interruption of communications with the Solution (see Section 2.6.2), shall be automatically transferred and loaded into the Solution once communications are restored.

Regardless of communication, data is stored continuously within the Stinson AIS Bluetooth and Wi-Fi sensor, encrypted on an onboard SD card. Data may be retrieved via the sensors web-based GUI:

 

When ITS Central detects the restoration of communication to the sensor, it automatically downloads the archived data files needed from the sensor, and re-process the Bluetooth/WiFi data by matching with data from other sensors, and re-computing the travel time data.

 

4.5 The Solution shall be capable of configuring Bluetooth reader settings, including: Bluetooth reader ID as assigned by MTO; System-related functions, including data storage, and user authentication; Network-related parameters, including IP address, netmask, and gateway; Time synchronization between the travel time server and Bluetooth Readers; and other features required to make the Proponents Bluetooth Readers operational.

ITS Central and the sensors web-based GUI allows for configuration of the Bluetooth reader settings, including assignment of the ID, system related functions, data storage, user authentication, network parameters, time synchronization, and other factory features.

 

 

 

4.6 The Bluetooth Readers shall be configured such that the Vendor receives a notification immediately upon Bluetooth device failure.

Field devices are monitored by ITS Central, and email notifications are sent immediately to B&Ms team as well as any other persons included in the notification list - immediately upon Bluetooth device failure.

 

 

 

4.7 The Solution shall record details of any Bluetooth device configuration changes.

All device configuration changes are recorded, including the username of the person who made the change, type of change, and the time, under the Edit History tab of the device details page, available for all devices.

 

 

4.8 The Media Access Control (MAC) IDs of all captured Bluetooth-enabled devices shall be encrypted automatically based on industry standard encryption and privacy requirements.

The MAC IDs captured by the Bluetooth readers are encrypted using a cryptographically secure one-way hash function in order to satisfy privacy requirements.

When ITS Central detects the restoration of communication to the sensor (regardless if it is an origin, destination or intermediate reader), it automatically downloads the archived data files needed from the sensor, and re-process the Bluetooth/Wi-Fi data by matching with data from other sensors, and re-computing the travel time data.

Data Feed Configuration

 

5.3.1. The Solution shall generate three (3) real-time secured data feeds: Link-based TT TT between two adjacent BT; Route-based TT TT between VMS and the displayed destination; and Sign-based TT message for each destination defined for VMS.

ITS Central does not distinguish between routes or links, in that both routes and links are calculated using the same travel time algorithm. The ITS Central Travel Time calculation works for both the Link and Route based XML feeds. Once the locations of the Bluetooth Readers, VMS signs, and route destinations are configured, the XML feeds will fully comply with the specifications.

ITS Central allows MTO to define a configurable time period during which MTO will publish route travel time messages on VMS.  The initial default time period shall be: Weekdays (Monday to Friday) 6:00am to 10:00am, 3:00pm to 8:00pm; and Weekends (Saturday and Sunday) and statutory holidays 9:00am to 12:00pm, 5:00pm to 9:00pm.  These time periods are easily configurable as illustrated by the screenshot below.

1.15.3.6 OPERATIONS, WARRANTY AND MAINTENANCE PLAN

1.15.3.6.1 OPERATIONS AND MAINTENANCE PLAN

Black & McDonald (B&M) will be responsible for System Operational Support, Warranty, System Emergency Repairs, and System Routine Maintenance for the TT system. B&M will maintain fault free operation of the TT system including the hardware and software parts as well as maintaining effective working conditions according to the contracts specifications. B&M project management team will review the restrictions outline in Appendix C3 and create a maintenance plan based on information provided. The maintenance team will carry out successful coordination with any other contractors to stay away from working in the same area by providing the advanced notice to the contract administrator or representative from general contractors. All activities will follow the requirements specified in the Service Level Agreement to ensure equipment and system performance levels are met throughout the life of the Contract.

a)    Plan for meeting system performance requirements outlined in the Service Level Agreement

Black & McDonald and the project team will meet all the system performance requirements outlined in the Service Level Agreement. A detailed plan is mentioned below in the following section. Plan will be developed by experienced staff working with high tech applications as well as maintenance. Our staff has great understanding on the importance of emergency response to meet the contract requirements on one hand, and make sure they are performing their task in the safest manner on the other hand. A detailed Routine Maintenance Plan as well as Emergency Maintenance Plan are outlined in part b below.

b)    How the Proponent will operate, maintain, and report on status of the system

Plan for Reporting on System Status:

During the operational and maintenance phases of the contract, Black & McDonald will be responsible for monitoring the operation of all ITS components including BT readers installed under the contract. B&M will immediately notify the MTO if any MTO-supplied material or equipment (existing or new) is discovered to be broken or faulty, affecting system performance. Field devices will be monitored by ITS Central, and notifications will be sent to B&M if a device failure is detected. In line with the Agreement, the MTO will decide on a course of action with respect to such material or equipment. When Black & McDonald Limited is notified of an occurrence, it must respond within the specified time frame. Any incidents will be documented in detail and reported to the MTO, with a summary of the root cause and corrective action taken. In the event that road closures are required for routine maintenance or emergency repairs, B&M will notify the MTO prior to the start of work. If an ITS component is experiencing any sort of failure, the following resolution procedure will be followed, depending on the type of error reported. Any failures of components will be documented. Spot checks will be performed on components that have previously failed and been brought back to functionality. The following components will be checked as part of the ITS component spot checks:

         BT Readers: Field crews will conduct spot checks to ensure BT readers are online, aligned and communicating valid data to the network. BT readers can be checked by confirming status LEDs on front of unit. Ethernet cables on the sensor, POE and modem can be checked to ensure snug and seated. Antenna coax connections on the sensor & modem can be checked to ensure tightness, external omni antennas can also be checked to confirm snug and tight. Field crews will contact B&M support for any BT readers related issues found during a spot check. BT Readers will be monitored by ITS Central, and notifications will be sent to B&M if a device failure is detected.

Sensors can also be accessed remotely to confirm web interface is functional and responsive. From the web server active detections from Bluetooth, Bluetooth LE and Wi-Fi devices and be observed & verified through its live view.

         Modems: Field crews will confirm modems are online and communicating valid data. Crews will observe LEDs on the modem to confirm data is being received and transferred. In the event a fault is detected, crews will be directed to re-boot the component and have B&M support access the device remotely to confirm its back online.

         Power Supply:

o   AC systems will be fed by the traffic cabinet supply, measuring supply voltage will confirm normal power voltage conditions.

o   Solar systems can be checked to ensure solar input voltage and battery voltage are within expected tolerances (18V and ~13 to 14V respectively).

 

Servers will be hosted professionally and reliably by OVH; onsite technician, security backup power supply, and redundant network connection will enhance the operational reliability. Transnomis will perform routine server update for operating system and security patches.

TASK 4 TT System Routine Maintenance

Purpose

To provide routine maintenance services in accordance with the requirements of the project agreement.

Approach and Methodology

System Routine Maintenance Services:

Routine maintenance services will be scheduled in accordance to the approved Scheduled System Maintenance Plan. It will be conducted for all TT system components within the contract limits. Routine maintenance and inspection services will comply with the Equipment Specific Scheduled Maintenance Requirements outline in the SLA, manufacture recommendations and be in accordance with the ITS elements and operation and maintenance manuals. Any ITS maintenance work related to the upgrade of system components will be reviewed by approved MTO consultants and all products used for upgrades will meet the applicable project agreement requirements, in accordance with the Designated Source Material (DSM) List. Maintenance services will be mobilized from the B&M closest yard. Prior to mobilization, B&M will coordinate with the MTO for any traffic management requests to avoid disrupting any other MTO contractors operations. Unspecified conditions such as accidents, stalled vehicles, etc. will be taken into account prior to mobilization. If such conditions exist or occur causing disruption to regularly scheduled maintenance activities, this will be communicated to the MTO and an appropriate alternate mobilization strategy will be provided. B&M will mobilize the necessary manpower, equipment and traffic control devices based on the routine maintenance required for that site. All traffic control devices will be setup in accordance to MTO Book 7 procedures. Upon arriving on site we will notify the MTO and then conduct a workplace safety & environmental protection briefing based on our analysis of the site. All hazard will be addressed immediately and no preventable conditions causing a hazard will exist. Routine maintenance activities will then be executed in accordance to the approved Scheduled System Maintenance Plan. Maintenance reports will be completed in detail. Upon completion, we will clean the job site of any garbage or debris, record maintenance activity and sign and date the log book, dismantle traffic control and notify the MTO of the work that was completed and that we are leaving the site. A follow up ESA inspection will be scheduled if required to inspect any electrical work that was done and a copy of the report will be kept on file. Pictures of specific problems will be taken if necessary with corrective direction.

System Software Maintenance Services and Support: Software updates will be rolled out to the TT System to enhance performance, resolve system bugs and to address requests for system changes. Software bugs will be identified by system operators (self-identification), automated system performance reports and user feedback. A ticketing system will be implemented to maintain a monthly log of issues and resolution timelines. Upon ticket resolution, the root cause of the software issue will be documented and included in the ticket close-out. System software assistance will be provided for MTO operators in the event it is requested. Written notice to the MTO for approval of any scheduled routine maintenance impacting operations or requiring full system outage will be provided at least two (2) weeks in advance. Any software routine maintenance requiring full system outage will be conducted between 10:00 am and 3:00 pm pending prior notification and approval.

System Enhancements: Modifications to enhance the functionality of the TT System will be implemented as they become available over the duration of the SLA. Any new features or functionalities added to the system will be communicated though software release notes. The release version of the software will be updated to include the latest enhancement.

Key Deliverables

  Obtain all necessary permits prior to mobilization

TASK 3 Respond to Emergency Maintenance

Purpose

To provide emergency maintenance and repairs for all devices listed in the contract, in accordance to the required timeframes.

Approach and Methodology

The on-call crew will be briefed on the category of the call and sent after receiving an emergency call at either the 24/7 hour dispatch center or via the list of contacts provided to the MTO. On-call crew will have access to a service truck and some supplies from their home base. If more material or equipment is needed, one crew member will go to the yard to obtain supplies or spare parts, while another crew member will go to the job site to assess the situation and deal with any urgent dangers. All replacements components related to ITS will be compatible with the implemented TT system. The use replacement components will be in accordance to the Ontario Ministry DSM list. Response time on site will be less than four hours for all critical failures, less than six hours for major failures and less than twelve hours for minor failures.

Upon receiving the emergency call, traffic control measures will be coordinated based on the necessity of it. Hazards will be addressed immediately and no preventable conditions causing a Hazard will exist. After adopting proper safety precautions, an evaluation report of the failure will be provided to the MTO, along with an expected time to perform temporary or permanent repairs. Before beginning any work that necessitates the replacement of ITS components, crews will seek approval from the MTO. To restore system operation, emergency maintenance/repairs will be performed. Permanent repairs will be conducted within 10 days if temporary repairs were made to restore functionality. The MTO will be advised of the work done and the crew's departure time after temporary or permanent repairs are completed. The following information will be recorded in the non-routine log book by the on-call crew: When on-call workers were notified of the ITS malfunction or failure, when they arrived on site, and when the repair was finished and the component was restored to full functionality.

1.15.3.6.2 SYSTEM REDUNDANCY PROCEDURE

 

BT Reader Redundancy

The Stinson AIS has a number of redundancy features which helps ensure data integrity and greater system uptime and availability. These include:

         Onboard SD Card with Self-Healing The onboard SD card stores all detection data locally in raw format (after hashing/encryption). If the sensor loses connection to the central software it will continue to detect devices and record their unique IDs locally on the SD card, upon restoration of the network connection the software system will pull all missing data from the SD card and fill any gaps in the data.

         Redundant Detection Radios As the AIS uses two separate radio transceivers (1 Bluetooth, 1 WiFi) for detection, even if one of those devices were to fail the other radio would continue detecting. Thus, allowing the travel time path integrity to be maintained.

         Remote Access and Reset The AIS can be remotely reset from its onboard web interface allowing for remote troubleshooting before attending site. The status of various run-time services such as the BT detection service and the WiFi detection service can also be viewed from the web interface allowing one to force restart them if one is not operating correctly. Software services monitoring and diagnostics are useful tools for remote troubleshooting.

         Standardized Device Settings The proposed architecture of providing a sensor & cell modem in each cabinet allows for the AIS sensor LAN IP addresses to be set the same in each system, while relying on the cell modem to provide a unique public static IP. This makes device swaps extremely quick and easy as no configuration is required on the sensor, they are very much plug and play.

System Redundancy and Failover

A total of 3 servers, hosted professionally by OVH within Canada, will be utilized in this project to achieve full system triple redundancy and fail-over.

OVH has technician and security on-site 24/7. It has systematic double power supply, 250 kVA UPS and generators with an initial autonomy of 48 hours. It has a minimum of 2 network connections and two network rooms within each of its data centers.

In addition to the primary server, an identical software installation will be created in two additional servers one for failover and one for hot spare. The database will be set up with streaming replication such that the databases in all three (3) servers will always be in sync. In the event the primary server fails, the secondary server can quickly and automatically take over to become the primary server. Transnomis will then reconfigure streaming replication such that the secondary server will stream to the tertiary server, and reconfigure the failover to be the tertiary server. The failed server will then be replaced.

A Watch Dog process will be installed in the primary and secondary servers to monitor each other in order to detect if the other server has crashed. If the primary server detects an issue on the secondary server, a system issue will be logged so that the secondary server problem can be investigated. If the secondary server detects a catastrophic issue with the primary server, and it does not recover within a configurable period of time, the Watch Dog process will log the issue and instruct the secondary server to take over the operation as the primary server.

The Watch Dog process will ensure that between the primary and secondary servers, ITS Central will be highly available with no more than 10 minutes downtime should there be any system failures with the primary server.

Database replication is a built-in feature of PostgreSQL. In particular, PostgreSQL supports Logical Replication. An excerpt from the PostgreSQL user manual describing Logical Replication is provided below:

Logical replication is a method of replicating data objects and their changes, based upon their replication identity (usually a primary key). We use the term logical in contrast to physical replication, which uses exact block addresses and byte-by-byte replication. PostgreSQL supports both mechanisms concurrently, see Chapter 26. Logical replication allows fine-grained control over both data replication and security.

Logical replication uses a publish and subscribe model with one or more subscribers subscribing to one or more publications on a publisher node. Subscribers pull data from the publications they subscribe to and may subsequently re-publish data to allow cascading replication or more complex configurations.

Logical replication of a table typically starts with taking a snapshot of the data on the publisher database and copying that to the subscriber. Once that is done, the changes on the publisher are sent to the subscriber as they occur in real-time. The subscriber applies the data in the same order as the publisher so that transactional consistency is guaranteed for publications within a single subscription. This method of data replication is sometimes referred to as transactional replication.

All servers will have the exact same database and software setup.

The primary server (initially SERVER A) is set up with a publication. On server start up, the secondary server (initially SERVER B) checks that the publication is ready if not, it will wait until the primary server is ready. When the publication is ready, the secondary and tertiary servers will subscribe to the publication and live replication will become active.

The diagram shown in Appendix D is a detailed flowchart of the high availability/automatic failover setup between only the primary server (master in the diagram) and secondary server (replica in the diagram). The failover logical flow is implemented using a Watch Dog process running independently of all other ITS Central processes (i.e., not sharing any code), removing all possibilities of bugs in the ITS Central code base affecting the Watch Dog process.

The Watch Dog in the secondary server monitors the following critical processes in the primary server:

         IP address by pinging the primary server periodically

         Web service (GUI) by polling the web interface

         PostgreSQL database by pinging the primary servers database

The Watch Dog on the secondary server will failover if:

         the primary server turns off due to power failure or other reasons;

         the primary servers NIC have problems which will lead to failure in the primary and secondary servers; and/or

         the primary server experiences a database failure, which can result from out of memory or out of disk space conditions.

However, the failover will be put on hold if any of the following conditions is detected:

         The secondary server cannot reach the primary server, but can reach web GUI.

         The secondary server cannot reach the primary server nor reference the device on the network. This means there is a problem with the internal network.

Once failover is completed, the new primary server will send the Project Team an email. The project team will investigate the failure and take the appropriate actions to resolve the failure, such as replacing the failed server.
